00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:11.750
Bodoni, all right.

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:18.860
Born in Saluzzo in Piemonte
which is Northwest Italy in 1740.

00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:25.180 position:56%
He apprenticed in Rome and then he
spent his professional life in Parma

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:29.370
which is in north central Italy.

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:33.490
This is a town in which he was
born and it's absolutely gorgeous.

00:04:33.490 --> 00:04:38.810
It's off the beaten path
and if you walk up any

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:43.180
of the narrow little streets
you'll see this massive mountain

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:44.540
which is called Monte Viso.

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:47.610
It's the highest mountain
in the Cottian Alps

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:51.790
and it has three sources
of the River Po.

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:55.000
They join together as they
come off the mountain.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:01.730
They go through Saluzzo and
then the mighty Po makes its way

00:05:01.730 --> 00:05:09.240 position:56%
across the entire north of Italy and
eventually mouths into the Adriatic.

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:15.940
This is the house in which he
was born and any speak Italian?

00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:18.750
Well, if you did you
would understand

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:25.320 position:56%
that it is now a dry cleaners, a dry
cleaning and dying establishment.

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:28.800
The plaque on the wall here
tells you that his date

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:33.580
of birth is February the
26th not the 16th as recorded

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:37.720 position:56%
by his principal Italian biographer.

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:41.620
So I think this is right.

00:05:41.620 --> 00:05:46.960
Here's Bodoni's grandfather on the
left and his father on the right.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:50.130
He came from a family
of printers even

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:52.580
on his mother's side
there was printing.

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:59.710 position:56%
His grandfather before him went to
Rome to get training and his father,

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:06.080
I don't think his father actually
went to Rome, but try to remember

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:10.420
that style of printing on
the right his father's style

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:12.680
and you will see it again.

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:19.110 position:56%
This is the schoolroom, well this is
the school in which Bodoni studied

00:06:19.110 --> 00:06:23.500
in Saluzzo and I understand
that in the winter

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:29.890
when it was very cold they would
put waxed paper over the windows

00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:34.070
in order to see and you
imagine it is pretty cold

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:39.110
up near Monte Viso in the winter.

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:46.450
When he was 17, nearly 18,
he and a good friend decided

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:49.580 position:56%
that they would go and conquer Rome.

00:06:49.580 --> 00:06:53.870
Bodoni wanted to become the
greatest printer who ever lived

00:06:53.870 --> 00:06:57.780
and his friend wanted to become
the greatest servant of God

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:03.790
who ever lived so off they set
these two boys and made a journey

00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:09.570
which was described as one of
the writers in Italian about him

00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:15.210
as arduous and fatiguing to
Rome as indeed I'm sure it was

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:19.260
to get, to travel in those days.

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:27.500
So they arrived in Rome and found
it very difficult to find work

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:30.530
and it was really challenging

00:07:30.530 --> 00:07:34.310
and in fact beyond
protopriest went back home

00:07:34.310 --> 00:07:38.340
where he did become a parish
priest and they remained in touch.

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:42.410
Bodoni hung on and
eventually he found his way

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:44.900
to the College of the
Propaganda Fide.

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:50.850
The Propaganda Fide being the
missionary arm of the Vatican

00:07:50.850 --> 00:07:55.720
and thus an establishment that
printed Bibles and Missals

00:07:55.720 --> 00:08:00.150
in exotic languages in order to
convert people in the Middle East

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:05.200
and the Far East, so
already there was exotic type

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:09.300
at the Propaganda Fide
when Bodoni arrived.

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:14.560
He's so impressed Cardinal
Spinelli who was the head

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:21.740 position:56%
of the Propaganda Fide with his
little wood engravings he took these

00:08:21.740 --> 00:08:27.880
along as samples of what he
could do and the story goes

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:33.020
that Cardinal Spinelli gave
him a test, asked him to design

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:38.200
and cut a Coat of Arms in a
couple of hours or something.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:42.810
Well Bodoni of course managed
and he was hired on the spot.

00:08:42.810 --> 00:08:47.660
Spinelli also took him into
his own home which happened

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:53.050 position:56%
to be the Palazzo Valentini which is
the building on the right side here.

00:08:53.050 --> 00:08:56.360
So Bodoni just imagine he was
up in you know lowly apprentice,

00:08:56.360 --> 00:09:01.800
you know up in one of those
sky lit rooms up top there.

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:05.480
So in the morning he could
roll out of bed and just walk

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:13.020 position:56%
down into the Forum of Trajan and
finds himself face-to-face with some

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:19.500
of the most important
lettering every cut.

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:25.570
His first tasks, no
not his first task.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:26.940
He started very low.

00:09:26.940 --> 00:09:30.490
He did anything you know he
was kind if dog's body there

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:36.490
but he eventually started composing
and the first book he worked

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:41.570
on was what's called a
Pontificale, a book for Bishops

00:09:41.570 --> 00:09:46.440
of services the Bishops would give

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:52.430
and this is actually quite
interesting and rare.

00:09:52.430 --> 00:09:59.230
On the left you have the first run,
Bodoni's first run at doing this

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:03.300
and so it's printed in two colors.

00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:07.990
It's printed in two
languages Coptic and Arabic.

00:10:07.990 --> 00:10:13.970
The powers that be were so
impressed by what he could do

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:18.220
that they then went on to print
lots more copies and allowed him

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:21.850
to sign his name, no
to print his name.

00:10:21.850 --> 00:10:24.090
It's not his signature, to
print his name at the bottom

00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:26.540
which was very unusual
for a lowly typesetter

00:10:26.540 --> 00:10:30.690
but they were so pleased about it.

00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:35.240
Now the one on the left is actually
in the Houghton Library at Harvard

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:43.810 position:56%
and it's quite a big book and it has
in pencil written in it "very rare."

00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:49.120
So I was absolutely fascinated
because I went back to Parma

00:10:49.120 --> 00:10:55.840
in February and presented the book
which was a wonderful moment for me

00:10:55.840 --> 00:10:59.450
to go back to the city
where I'd worked so hard

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:03.290
with an actual product
which I'm not convinced

00:11:03.290 --> 00:11:08.130
that they thought I was
capable of doing but I did.

00:11:08.130 --> 00:11:11.360
So I showed this image
and they had never seen it

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:17.740
so it is indeed very
rare the one on the left.

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:23.500
Bodoni worked for six years in Rome

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:27.230
and then you know how
things come together

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:31.740
to make you make some
kind of move in life?

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:38.760
Cardinal Spinelli died and Bodoni's
immediate superior Abbe Ruggieri

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:47.430
killed himself, shot himself and
this was a terrible, terrible thing

00:11:47.430 --> 00:11:53.970
for Bodoni because they
were very close and Bodoni,

00:11:53.970 --> 00:11:59.930
Ruggieri was depressant and but
he found relief from depression

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:01.290
in the company of Bodoni.

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:06.730
Bodoni was very vibrant and so
Bodoni in the mornings would go

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:13.920
over to the, to Abbe Ruggieri's
home and he would wait for him

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:16.830
until he was ready and then
they would walk together

00:12:16.830 --> 00:12:18.800
to the Propaganda Fide.

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:21.030
On this morning Bodoni went over.

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:26.560 position:56%
The servant told him that Abbe was
not ready and then there was a sound

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:29.950
of the shot and he
had killed himself.

00:12:29.950 --> 00:12:34.080
Now if you think about the
circumstances there how terrible

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:38.620
that must have been for
Bodoni and you wonder

00:12:38.620 --> 00:12:43.930
about Ruggieri's motivation
in killing himself

00:12:43.930 --> 00:12:49.110
at that very moment it's kind of
one of these unsolved mysteries

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:54.030
but it set Bodoni up for
wanting to leave Rome.

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:59.230
On the brighter side Bodoni had
met quite a few English tourists

00:12:59.230 --> 00:13:06.960 position:56%
in Rome, part of the grand tour they
were there also carting goods back

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:13.930
to England to museums and to their
stately homes in England from Italy

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:17.790
and then had told him that there
are things happening in England.

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:20.580
There's quite a lot of
innovation going on.

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:25.810 position:56%
There's this chap called Baskerville
and Bodoni thought, yeah, I better.

00:13:25.810 --> 00:13:27.230
I want to stretch my wings.

00:13:27.230 --> 00:13:29.970
I will go to England.

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:31.970
Never mind that I didn't
speak English.

00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:36.300
Everybody in England was speaking
Italian because they liked opera.

00:13:37.710 --> 00:13:42.600
So off he went and he decided that
he would stop and see his parents

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:46.570
on the way in Saluzzo because
it's near directly north

00:13:46.570 --> 00:13:51.760
and then he would go on to
England but on the way he fell ill.

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:57.610
And we think it was malaria and
he was quite ill so he went home

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:00.680
to his mother and she
took care of him

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:06.000
and when he recovered he started
working again with his father

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.020
in the family printworks.

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:16.460
Until the meantime in Parma the
young 18 year-old Duke of Parma

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:25.630 position:56%
and his wonderfully attractive Prime
Minister Guillaume Du Tillot wanted

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:32.910
to put Parma on the map and how
did you do that in those days?

00:14:32.910 --> 00:14:38.850
Well you did that by setting
up a printworks in your city

00:14:38.850 --> 00:14:41.690
so that you could advertise
your city

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:47.260
as being quite the most marvelous
and charming place in Italy.

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:51.290
But how could they go about this?

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:57.550
How could they set out to
just start a printworks

00:14:57.550 --> 00:15:00.740
and a press from nothing?

00:15:00.740 --> 00:15:04.700 position:56%
Well, Guillaume Du Tillot being
French consulted a great connoisseur

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:08.760
in Paris called Pierre-Jean
Mariette.

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:16.330 position:56%
Pierre-Jean Mariette was a wise man
and he said do not hire a Frenchman.

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:18.330 position:56%
Hire an Italian because you're going

00:15:18.330 --> 00:15:20.520
to be printing a lot
of works in Italian.

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:23.750
If you want to get them
right hire Italian.

00:15:23.750 --> 00:15:30.720
The problem was there were no
Italian's suitable for the job,

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:43.830
so there was a librarian, ha, ha,
ha in Parma Paulo Maria Paciaudi

00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:46.180
who had known Bodoni in Rome

00:15:46.180 --> 00:15:49.180
and coincidentally they
were both from Piedmont.

00:15:49.180 --> 00:15:55.200
They were both Piedmontese and
they stick together Piedmontese

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:59.640
so he said, "I've met
this young man in Rome

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:03.510
and he is incredibly talented.

00:16:03.510 --> 00:16:05.160
He is absolutely superb."

00:16:05.160 --> 00:16:10.280
And by this time Bodoni
had cut some punches.

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:13.900
He had designed typer pages.

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:16.880
He had worked with exotic type.

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:21.920
In fact while he was in Rome he
was sent to La Sapienza University

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:25.740
of Rome where he studied
Hebrew and Arabic

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:31.340
and so he had working knowledge
of some exotic languages

00:16:31.340 --> 00:16:37.200
and Paciaudi said, "I
think he would do."

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:42.080
So the Duke and the Prime
Minister sent off the invitation

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:48.680
and in February, 1768
Bodoni arrived in Parma.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:53.690
They set up the printworks
and his apartment above.

00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:57.800
That's called the Palazzo
della Pilotta

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:03.710
and it's an extraordinary building
built by the Farnese family

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:12.280
which includes the Farnese Theater
which is absolutely gigantic

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:16.540
and they could produce,
they could flood the floor

00:17:16.540 --> 00:17:19.740
and produce naval battles in it.

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:22.110
It's quite an extraordinary place.

00:17:22.110 --> 00:17:28.000 position:56%
So Bodoni could print something
off, cross the bridge over the river

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:35.000 position:56%
and arrive at the ducal palace to
show the Duke anything that you know

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.050
if he needed his approval.

00:17:39.050 --> 00:17:44.820
Bodoni liked his food.

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:50.220
He had come from Rome
where the food is very kind

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:53.810
of vegetable-aised,
olive oil, very healthy.

00:17:53.810 --> 00:17:59.160
Parma on the other hand,
you've heard of Parma ham?

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:01.710
You've heard of Parma cheese?

00:18:01.710 --> 00:18:08.560
It's a very, very protein
driven diet mostly pork.

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:12.770
There's a lot of pork
and of course oh,

00:18:12.770 --> 00:18:16.400
I meant to tell you that's
tortelli di erbette which is a sort

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:20.730
of ravioli-like pasta that contains
Swiss chard or wheat greens.

00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:24.590
Do you know what we have here?

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:29.400
Can you tell what we
have here on the left?

