Yes, we do indeed have
the sausage maker.

00:18:33.300 --> 00:18:36.690
So this is in the 11th
century baptistery so already

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:41.100
in Parma they were
devoted to their salami.

00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:45.600
When Bodoni arrived he brought,
I think he brought a few punches

00:18:45.600 --> 00:18:47.690
of his own but there was nothing.

00:18:47.690 --> 00:18:56.650
There was nothing in Parma so
he had to order type from France

00:18:56.650 --> 00:19:02.620
and his great hero in
printing was Fournier

00:19:02.620 --> 00:19:06.650
and so he ordered Fournier type.

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:14.010
So in the beginning Bodoni is
Fournier and gradually as time went

00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:21.020
on Fournier became Bodoni.

00:19:21.020 --> 00:19:24.060
This I think you will
feel reminds you

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:31.090
of his father's work is still
old-fashioned his father's work.

00:19:31.090 --> 00:19:36.280
So this is the very first thing
he actually printed in Parma

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:43.810
of substance and it is it's
essentially a poem of thanksgiving

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:52.510 position:56%
for the recovery from once again,
malaria of Prime Minister Du Tillot.

00:19:52.510 --> 00:20:03.210 position:56%
The next big work was a presentation
volume for the marriage of the Duke

00:20:03.210 --> 00:20:10.840
of Parma, 18 years old with
this Duchess of Austria,

00:20:10.840 --> 00:20:15.130
one of the 16 children of
Maria Theresa of Austria.

00:20:15.130 --> 00:20:19.500
At this point Maria
Theresa had a rather a lot

00:20:19.500 --> 00:20:25.090
of marriageable daughters that
she needed to get out in the world

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:30.060
so she sent this one to Parma
to marry the Duke of Parma.

00:20:30.060 --> 00:20:35.940
She sent Marie Antoinette to Paris
to marry the [inaudible] of France

00:20:35.940 --> 00:20:41.020
and Carolina to Naples to
marry the king of Naples.

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:45.810
This one as you can probably
tell is a piece of work.

00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:54.100
She very often she
Austrianized Parma.

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:56.800
She got rid of Guillaume Du Tillot

00:20:56.800 --> 00:21:02.510
and it became a very different
place while she was there.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:06.310
Anyway, to go back to this
fabulous presentation volume

00:21:06.310 --> 00:21:12.450 position:56%
that they produced in celebration of
the wedding Bodoni worked in concert

00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:15.830
with Petitot who was an architect.

00:21:15.830 --> 00:21:19.520
He had come to Parma to
brighten the face of Parma,

00:21:19.520 --> 00:21:24.670
to build a few new buildings
and to kind of rehab others

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:31.490
and he was very gifted and he
and Bodoni worked hand and glove

00:21:31.490 --> 00:21:39.430 position:56%
on the book that you will see at the
bottom of this picture on the left.

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:44.690
Petitot was so pleased
with the finished volume

00:21:44.690 --> 00:21:51.860 position:56%
that he produced a funny little book
called "Masquerade a'la Grecque"

00:21:51.860 --> 00:21:55.870
in which everybody in it is dressed
up in some sort of Greek outfit.

00:21:55.870 --> 00:22:00.340
Anyway, there's the book again up
on the left on top of the column

00:22:00.340 --> 00:22:04.830
and here's the title page.

