but it's a facsimile.

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:12.300
He had six presses going at one
point, at one time and but none

00:26:12.300 --> 00:26:19.190
of them remain but they managed
to get a facsimile of one of them.

00:26:19.190 --> 00:26:21.860
This book is over on that table.

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:28.130
I'm very pleased that
we can see that book.

00:26:28.130 --> 00:26:33.080
An Epithalamia is a book written
in celebration of a wedding

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:40.230
and the wedding was that of the
prince of Piedmont so we're back

00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:44.800
in Piedmont royalty among
Piedmontese and the prince

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:48.620
of Piedmont married Marie
Clotilde, the Princess of France,

00:26:48.620 --> 00:26:57.500
a princess of France so Bodoni
produced another marvelous

00:26:57.500 --> 00:27:04.260
presentation volume and in what he
did in it was he had 26 pages each

00:27:04.260 --> 00:27:10.320 position:56%
with a different language, different
exotic type and the iconography

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:15.340
for the city that it
represented, the city in Piemonte

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:21.500
that it represented so this is the
page for Saluzzo for his hometown.

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:29.110 position:56%
For some reason he chose to use
Armenian as the script and the image

00:27:29.110 --> 00:27:34.100
above is of, it's actually got
rivers you know the tributaries

00:27:34.100 --> 00:27:40.820
of the Po and various other
items of interest to Saluzzo.

00:27:40.820 --> 00:27:47.660 position:56%
That particular book made such an
impression on the Spanish ambassador

00:27:47.660 --> 00:27:59.630 position:56%
who lived in Rome but came to Parma
and was astounded by Bodoni's talent

00:27:59.630 --> 00:28:05.720 position:56%
and he felt very, very strongly that
Bodoni was wasting himself in Parma

00:28:05.720 --> 00:28:10.170
when he should be actually in Rome.

00:28:10.170 --> 00:28:13.660
He felt that Bodoni
was printing ephemera.

00:28:13.660 --> 00:28:21.230
He was printing announcements,
invitations, playbills

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:25.310 position:56%
and silly sonnets for would-be poets

00:28:25.310 --> 00:28:29.090
who wanted their work
printed by the great Bodoni.

00:28:29.090 --> 00:28:33.030
And he said, "If you come
to Rome I will give you your

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:35.060
own establishment.

00:28:35.060 --> 00:28:38.280
You will publish the classics.

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:39.900
You will not have to do any

00:28:39.900 --> 00:28:44.590
of this essentially grunt
work and so come to Rome.

00:28:44.590 --> 00:28:47.170
Come to Rome."

00:28:47.170 --> 00:28:49.900
Well Bodoni liked Parma.

00:28:49.900 --> 00:28:53.440
He was comfortable in Parma.

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:59.590
However, in 1791 when the pressure
was really on from Azara to go

00:28:59.590 --> 00:29:02.750
to Rome and Bodoni was
beginning to weaken and think

00:29:02.750 --> 00:29:07.500
that you know it might be a good
idea the Duke heard about it

00:29:07.500 --> 00:29:14.660
and he really didn't want to let
Bodoni go because Bodoni was,

00:29:14.660 --> 00:29:17.300
well he was like a
rock star by this time.

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:19.480
He attracted people to Parma.

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:22.330
Tourists came to Parma
and they went first

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:25.420
to see Bodoni before they
paid tribute to the Duke.

00:29:25.420 --> 00:29:32.370
He was, it's hard to imagine
nowadays but it was you know it was

00:29:32.370 --> 00:29:36.900
like what's his name,
Steve Jobs, right?

00:29:36.900 --> 00:29:42.120
Somebody like that,
star quality, big name.

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:45.460
So the Duke said, "No,
I can't let you go.

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:48.270
You must stay here but
here's what I'll do.

00:29:48.270 --> 00:29:54.560 position:56%
I'll give you your own private press
so you can print anything you want

00:29:54.560 --> 00:29:58.280
as long as just stay here
and print what I want."

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:00.810
So that's the deal they cut.

00:30:00.810 --> 00:30:09.030
Well immediately Azara commissioned
him to producing "Horace"

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:18.720 position:56%
and now you see Bodoni doing what he
wanted expressing himself as Bodoni

00:30:18.720 --> 00:30:25.460
with his perfect balance, his black
ink on really good white paper,

00:30:25.460 --> 00:30:30.500 position:56%
his own recipe for his ink and he --

00:30:30.500 --> 00:30:35.940
so from then on his work
just got better and better.

00:30:35.940 --> 00:30:40.960
But there was another reason why
Bodoni wanted to stay in Parma.

00:30:40.960 --> 00:30:43.890
What do you think that was?

00:30:43.890 --> 00:30:49.180
Well you may be wondering
about romance in Bodoni's life.

00:30:49.180 --> 00:30:57.010
He's by now 51 and if you scratch
around trying to find anything,

00:30:57.010 --> 00:31:05.120 position:56%
any whiff of scandal that -- you can
make guesses and many certainly have

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:11.790
but you know as a biography you've
got to hew to the facts so anyway

00:31:11.790 --> 00:31:17.040
at the age of 51 he had begun
to suffer from the terrible gout

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:22.490
that pursued him for the rest
of his life and I think the idea

00:31:22.490 --> 00:31:26.840
of a little sort of home
comfort seemed really good.

00:31:26.840 --> 00:31:36.750
He had come to know this young
woman Margherita dall'Aglio

00:31:36.750 --> 00:31:46.270
but she was unfortunately engaged
to somebody else but Bodoni was

00:31:46.270 --> 00:31:52.140
so famous and so attractive
that she managed to get rid

00:31:52.140 --> 00:32:00.450
of the other guy so
they got married.

00:32:00.450 --> 00:32:06.460
The little chapel in which
they got married in Parma

00:32:06.460 --> 00:32:16.660
but all was not entirely right
in this big year of 1791.

00:32:16.660 --> 00:32:24.930
Bodoni had had metal
workers from San Pancrazio

00:32:24.930 --> 00:32:31.440 position:56%
which is a village outside Parma who
proved to be really useful working

00:32:31.440 --> 00:32:39.200
with him two brothers and a nephew
and this is murky territory right?

00:32:39.200 --> 00:32:40.720
This is murky territory.

00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:44.010
He taught them how to cut punches

00:32:44.010 --> 00:32:51.330
and so they were working alongside
him but they began to feel

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:52.980
that they were doing all this work

00:32:52.980 --> 00:32:56.160
but they weren't getting
the acknowledgement

00:32:57.820 --> 00:33:02.960
so there was a terrific
rift and they left

00:33:02.960 --> 00:33:07.660
and started their own
printworks in San Pancrazio.

00:33:07.660 --> 00:33:16.030 position:56%
So I thought it would be interesting
for you to see their work compared

00:33:16.030 --> 00:33:21.200
to Bodoni's and I think you
recognize the master, don't you?

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:30.010
Yeah. Round about the
same time Didot

00:33:30.010 --> 00:33:36.070
in France the great
French printer got hold

00:33:36.070 --> 00:33:38.590
of a copy of Bodoni's "Aeneid."

00:33:38.590 --> 00:33:47.360
Now he may have got a
hold of a final copy

00:33:47.360 --> 00:33:54.580
but Bodoni believed he had got
hold of an uncorrected proof

00:33:54.580 --> 00:34:02.670
and it's possible that the
Amoretti brothers had been the ones

00:34:02.670 --> 00:34:07.110
to get this uncorrected
proof to Paris.

00:34:07.110 --> 00:34:09.190
As I say this is murky stuff.

00:34:09.190 --> 00:34:12.140
It's not definitive.

00:34:12.140 --> 00:34:14.660 position:56%
Didot then produces his own "Aeneid"

00:34:14.660 --> 00:34:23.270 position:56%
and in the introduction he took
Bodoni to task and listed his typers

00:34:23.270 --> 00:34:28.680
which I think is actually
just about as cruel a thing

00:34:28.680 --> 00:34:31.580
as you can do to a competitor.

00:34:31.580 --> 00:34:38.420
However, in time they learned
to admire each other greatly

00:34:38.420 --> 00:34:42.350
and I'm not sure that
all was forgiven

00:34:42.350 --> 00:34:44.530
but certainly matters improved.

00:34:44.530 --> 00:34:50.460
I think Didot had to
back off a little bit

00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:56.900
when Bodoni won a very prestigious
prize for printing in France

00:34:56.900 --> 00:35:01.300
that no foreigner had ever one.

00:35:01.300 --> 00:35:08.910
He was a workaholic and if
he wasn't actually designing

00:35:08.910 --> 00:35:12.620
or printing he was cutting punches.

00:35:12.620 --> 00:35:16.740
He cut thousands and
thousands of punches

00:35:16.740 --> 00:35:21.960
but I think this is the
entrance of Senora Bodoni

00:35:21.960 --> 00:35:25.580
that they would have
conversation on Friday afternoons.

00:35:25.580 --> 00:35:29.790
They would gather their friends
together and enjoy themselves.

00:35:29.790 --> 00:35:33.090
I don't see any wine but maybe
it's a little early in the day

00:35:33.090 --> 00:35:37.770
but anyway it's a very
interesting image to read.

00:35:37.770 --> 00:35:43.890
On the far left you have Bodoni
and next to him is Giusepe de Lama

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:49.810
who would go on to write
the main biography,

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:54.200
the biography that people
always use and quote from

00:35:54.200 --> 00:36:00.990
but gets the birthday wrong
sorry, so they're clearly working

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:04.000
on something together maybe
Bodoni is telling him a bit

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:05.650
of his life's story.

00:36:05.650 --> 00:36:09.910
Behind them is DALMASTRO, the
manservant for the Bodoni's.

00:36:09.910 --> 00:36:16.190 position:56%
In the center are three good
friends from Parma rather well-born.

00:36:16.190 --> 00:36:17.490
One's a poet.

00:36:17.490 --> 00:36:18.790
One's a count.

00:36:18.790 --> 00:36:20.160
I forget what the third one is.

00:36:20.160 --> 00:36:26.110
Top right is Zambiagi the
foreman of the printworks and then

00:36:26.110 --> 00:36:33.260
down below [inaudible] slightly is
Signori Bodoni and Fernando Paer

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:38.730
who was a composer who
wrote the wedding march

00:36:38.730 --> 00:36:44.920
for Napoleon's second wedding.

00:36:44.920 --> 00:36:51.300
This is Rosaspina, Francesco
Rosaspina who was the one engraver

